    <!-- IN-DEPTH PERFORMANCE -->
    <section class="section">
      <h2 class="section-title">In-Depth Performance</h2>

      <div class="content-block">
        <h3>Low-Light Performance</h3>
        <p>
          This is the FX3's superpower. The 12MP full-frame sensor has massive photosites that collect incredible amounts of light. ISO 25,600 looks cleaner than most cameras at ISO 6400. You can shoot in near darkness and get usable, gradable footage. For documentary work, concerts, or nighttime cityscapes, the FX3 is unmatched.
        </p>
        <p>
          The sensor is the same as the A7S IIIâ€”Sony's legendary low-light champion. Extended ISO goes to 409,600, which is genuinely usable for extreme situations. Pair it with an f/1.4 lens, and you can film in conditions that would be impossible for any other camera.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="content-block">
        <h3>4K120 Slow Motion</h3>
        <p>
          Recording 4K at 120fps internally in 10-bit 4:2:2 is cinema-grade capability. The slow-motion footage is stunningâ€”perfect for B-roll, action sequences, or emotional moments. There's a slight 1.1x crop at 4K120, but the quality is still exceptional. The rolling shutter is more visible than at lower frame rates but manageable with proper technique.
        </p>
        <p>
          For standard 4K24/30/60 work ,the full sensor width is used with oversampling from 4.2K. This delivers incredibly sharp, detailed footage with minimal aliasing or moirÃ©. The 10-bit 4:2:2 codec gives massive grading latitude in post-production.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="content-block">
        <h3>Professional Audio</h3>
        <p>
          The included XLR handle is a game-changer. You can connect professional microphones, wireless systems, or boom mics directly to the camera. 4-channel recording means you can capture two separate audio sources simultaneously (e.g., lavalier + shotgun mic). Phantom power is onboard, and audio levels can be controlled via physical dials.
        </p>
        <p>
          For quick shoots without external audio gear, the built-in stereo microphones are surprisingly good. They're better than most mirrorless cameras and handle wind noise well. But the XLR handle is where the FX3 truly shines for professional work.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="content-block">
        <h3>Ergonomics & Cooling</h3>
        <p>
          The FX3's boxy cinema design is polarizing but functional. Multiple mounting points (no cage required) let you attach monitors, lights, and accessories directly. The built-in fan runs constantly, ensuring the camera never overheatsâ€”even during multi-hour 4K60 shoots in hot climates.
        </p>
        <p>
          The vari-angle touchscreen is excellent for high/low angles. No viewfinder means you'll need an external monitor for bright daylight work. But the cinema-focused design makes sense: this camera is built for rigs, gimbals, and professional setups, not run-and-gun handheld.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- IDEAL LENSES -->
    <section class="section">
      <h2 class="section-title">Ideal Lenses for the Sony FX3</h2>
      <div class="recommendations-grid">
        <div class="recommendation-card">
          <h4>Sony FE 24-70mm f/2.8 GM II</h4>
          <p>
            The ultimate cinema zoom. Constant f/2.8, silent focusing, near-zero breathing, and exceptional sharpness. Perfect for documentary work where you need flexibility without changing lenses.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="recommendation-card">
          <h4>Sony FE 35mm f/1.4 GM</h4>
          <p>
            Cinema prime perfection. The f/1.4 aperture pairs beautifully with the FX3's low-light sensor. Silky bokeh, pin-sharp center, and fast focusing for run-and-gun filmmaking.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="recommendation-card">
          <h4>Sigma Art Series (24mm, 35mm, 50mm, 85mm)</h4>
          <p>
            Budget-friendly cinema primes. Sigma's Art lenses deliver outstanding image quality, smooth bokeh, and robust build at half the price of Sony GM glass. Perfect for FX3 users building a prime set.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <section class="section">
      <h2>Sony FX3 FAQ</h2>

      <div class="faq-container">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>
            <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
              <span class="faq-icon"></span>
              What does Netflix-approved mean?
            </button>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>
              Netflix maintains a list of cameras approved for their original content productions. The FX3 meets their technical requirements for 4K capture, dynamic range, color depth, and codec quality. It's a stamp of professional credibility that places the FX3 alongside cameras costing $10,000+.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>
            <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
              <span class="faq-icon"></span>
              FX3 vs A7S IIIâ€”which should I buy?
            </button>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>
              They share the same sensor and image quality. The FX3 adds XLR audio, cinema body design, Active Mode stabilization, and tally lights. The A7S III has an EVF and better ergonom ics for photography. If you shoot 90%+ video, get the FX3. If you need hybrid capability, get the A7S III.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>
            <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
              <span class="faq-icon"></span>
              Is 12MP enough for video work?
            </button>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>
              Absolutely. 4K video only requires 8.3MP, so 12MP is plenty for oversampling. The lower resolution enables larger photosites, which dramatically improves low-light performance. This is a deliberate design choice prioritizing video quality over photo resolution.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>
            <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
              <span class="faq-icon"></span>
              Who should buy the Sony FX3?
            </button>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>
              Professional videographers, documentary filmmakers, commercial shooters, indie cinema directors, and content creators who demand cinema-grade quality. If you shoot video 90%+ of the time and need exceptional low-light, professional audio, and unlimited recording, the FX3 is built for you.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- FINAL RECOMMENDATION -->
